First of all, I loved the art style in this game. It was absolutely stunning and the gameplay was great. Highly recommend it on this count.  The bad is the background drain. I had installed and played a little bit of the game while my phone was on the charger. I stopped playing, let my phone finish charging to 100%, and then unplugged and went to bed.  In the morning, this app had used nearly 40% of my used battery! When investigating further, it not once used any CPU or anything, but it DID use 'Magnetic Field' for 10 hours. Further investigation led me to learn that this is mostly used in compass apps or apps that need access to a compass. Why does this run in the background all night when the app isn't even used? I have found no plausible explanation and until I can figure it out I must uninstall. It's too bad, I really liked this game.

The Market is awash with tower defense games, some good, some bad...  Jelly Defense is up there with the best of them.  the graphics are clean, bright, and imaginative.  the sounds and music offset the visuals perfectly.  The cutesy style had my other half opining "they should live together as they're so cute"  Gameplay is simple, and no different from any other similar game, so getting sharted is a breeze. However don't be fooled by the first few levels, the difficulty ramps up quite quickly.  later levels leave the player relying on trial and error, but this is surely what these types of games are about.  All in all, a really fine example of it's genre. and well worth the purchase price.  The only drawback is the quite eyewatering battery drain, my Galaxy Note managed about an hour of gameplay before it was begging to be plugged back into the wall.  Hence the fact I have time to write this rather than plugging away to completion.

You can see the dev spent quite a bit of effort into making this game look good, because it does look good.  However as far as tower defense games go, it's really sub-par.   First off, I always knock a star off from any TD game that makes me collect coins (or points, or whatever).  If you think the point of TD is to tap on (or swipe) the screen as fast possible to collect coins before they disappear then you shouldn't be making a defense game. Go make a kids game.  This is made worse by the fact that things get cramped quickly and half the time you go to collect your stupid coins a tower upgrade menu pops up instead.  Aside from that, the pace is slow, the towers poorly balanced (the range on some of the towers is just silly), and you quickly become annoyed and tired more than anything else.  I think the game would greatly improve if they made coin acquisition automatic and didn't make getting additional tower types take so long (and be so painful). A very average tower defense game with above average looks.
